As of my last update, Forge for Minecraft version 1.20.1 was not available, and so there is no existing code for that version. In addition, "1.20.1" may not reflect an actual release of Minecraft, as Minecraft versions are subject to Mojang’s own release schedule and versioning system. Minecraft Forge typically follows shortly after with compatible updates.

For the sake of providing a general idea of how one might add an options button using Forge (assuming a compatible version of Forge and Minecraft), here's an example of how you might set up a button in a GUI screen. This example will not match the version "1.20.1" specifically, but can serve as a starting point for modders using other versions. 

Please note that the following code is for educational purposes and is written to reflect Forge's modding API based on prior releases. Minecraft modding APIs change over time, and you should consult the latest Forge documentation for the correct methods and practices for your specific version.

```java
import net.minecraft.client.gui.screen.OptionsScreen;
import net.minecraft.client.gui.widget.button.Button;
import net.minecraft.client.gui.screen.Screen;
import net.minecraft.util.text.StringTextComponent;

public class CustomOptionsScreen extends OptionsScreen {

    public CustomOptionsScreen(Screen previousScreen) {
        super(previousScreen, Minecraft.getInstance().gameSettings);
    }

    @Override
    protected void init() {
        super.init();

        // Assuming the leave & save buttons have fixed positions, you'll want to place your new button relative to those.
        // This is just an example; you'll need to adjust the positions (x, y, width, height) based on the rest of your UI.

        this.addButton(new Button(this.width / 2 - 155, this.height / 6 - 12 + 24 * (4), 150, 20, new StringTextComponent("Beautiful Settings"), (button) -> {
            // Code to open the "Beautiful Settings" screen
            Minecraft.getInstance().displayGuiScreen(new BeautifulSettingsScreen(this));
        }));
    }
}

public class BeautifulSettingsScreen extends Screen {

    protected BeautifulSettingsScreen(Screen previousScreen) {
        super(new StringTextComponent("Beautiful Settings"));
        // Store the previousScreen if you need to return to it when this screen is closed
    }

    @Override
    protected void init() {
        super.init();

        // Initialize your custom settings UI here
    }

    // Handle other necessary overrides for button actions, rendering, etc.
}
```

To integrate the `CustomOptionsScreen`, you would also need to work with the event system in Forge to replace or modify the options screen, and create your `BeautifulSettingsScreen` class to handle your specific settings.

Since the exact implementation can greatly vary based on what you want your "Beautiful Settings" to do and the Forge/Minecraft version you are using, treat this code as a framework upon which to build.

If you're new to modding, or to Forge, start by setting up a proper modding environment, follow Forge's documentation closely, and participate in the modding community for up-to-date practices and code examples that are appropriate for the version of Minecraft you're targeting.
